Crj 450›chapter 2›››     The theme of chapter two discussed the history of police forces and how they were involved in corruption. It traced the history of police from its original concept in Old England to its adoption by American colonists. Next it told about the rise of municipal police. Then it talked about frontier justice and vigilantism then finally ending with policing in the twentieth century.›     Another theme of this chapter discussed police reform. Police reform started inthe late 20's and early 30's. Police reform had yet another revival in the 60's due to poor relations with minorities. This reform led to the philosophy of community policing.›      Police are designed as social control agents. They comprise the part of government that enforces the law on the public. In general policing had its origin in England. At first the people in the community were responsible for maintaining law and order amongst the community. AS time went on these policing forces made up of volunteers slowly evolved into a paid ppolice force under the guidance of SIr Robert peel in the 1820's, which is where we get the term "bobbies".›     We can trace the establishment of a police force in England to early police forces in America. In colonial times the first organized police force was night watchmen. However as the population grew, the need for a larger and paid police police force came about. BUt with this large police force came corruption. The police fell under the spoils system meaning that which ever political party was in charge could give political favors to the police to take "care" of their interests. It created political favoritism. Corruption was also present in the western frontier. Some people even took the law into their own hands. This is known as vigilantism. These vigilantes had no time to wait for the system to carry out proper justice.›     In the twentieth century, as police departments were the most corrupt and turnover rates for administrators were very high, it was time to bring about some kind of reform. One type of reform came about by the Civil Service Acts. Others came from the National Commission on Law Observance and Enforcement established by President Hoover. These acts not only established the abolition of corruption but to improve the police departments and also its officers in many ways. Another change that came about many years later was the improvement of relations with minorities. This was most prevalent in the 60's.›     These reforms is what brings us to better relations between the police and the public and thus the birth of community policing. Community policing involves the police and the community working together as one in order to solve the problems of the community and especially to improve relations between police and minorities.›     How this chapter applies to the concept of community policing is simple. It first traces the history of policing. Next it establishes that earlier police departments and law enforcing was replete with corruption. This corruption established the fact that reform was much needed. As a by-product of this reform came about community policing as a brand new philosophy in law enforcement.›     I found this chapter to be quite interesting. Especially the origins of police from old England. I was also surprised to learn of frontier justice and its blue laws that regulated social behavior but did little for serious crimes. 